modules.name: AWS.ECR
modules.comments: Amazon Elastic Container Registry (Amazon ECR) is a managed Docker registry service. Customers can use the familiar Docker CLI to push, pull, and manage images. Amazon ECR provides a secure, scalable, and reliable registry. Amazon ECR supports private Docker repositories with resource-based permissions using IAM so that specific users or Amazon EC2 instances can access repositories and images. Developers can use the Docker CLI to author and manage images.

declarations.comments:
Check the availability of multiple image layers in a specified registry and repository.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: batchCheckLayerAvailability

declarations.comments:
Deletes a list of specified images within a specified repository. Images are specified with either imageTag or imageDigest.

You can remove a tag from an image by specifying the image's tag in your request. When you remove the last tag from an image, the image is deleted from your repository.

You can completely delete an image (and all of its tags) by specifying the image's digest in your request.
declarations.title: batchDeleteImage

declarations.comments: Gets detailed information for specified images within a specified repository. Images are specified with either imageTag or imageDigest.
declarations.title: batchGetImage

declarations.comments:
Informs Amazon ECR that the image layer upload has completed for a specified registry, repository name, and upload ID. You can optionally provide a sha256 digest of the image layer for data validation purposes.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: completeLayerUpload

declarations.comments: Creates an image repository.
declarations.title: createRepository

declarations.comments: Deletes the specified lifecycle policy.
declarations.title: deleteLifecyclePolicy

declarations.comments: Deletes an existing image repository. If a repository contains images, you must use the force option to delete it.
declarations.title: deleteRepository

declarations.comments: Deletes the repository policy from a specified repository.
declarations.title: deleteRepositoryPolicy

declarations.comments:
Returns metadata about the images in a repository, including image size, image tags, and creation date.

Beginning with Docker version 1.9, the Docker client compresses image layers before pushing them to a V2 Docker registry. The output of the docker images command shows the uncompressed image size, so it may return a larger image size than the image sizes returned by DescribeImages.
declarations.title: describeImages

declarations.comments: Describes image repositories in a registry.
declarations.title: describeRepositories

declarations.comments:
Retrieves a token that is valid for a specified registry for 12 hours. This command allows you to use the docker CLI to push and pull images with Amazon ECR. If you do not specify a registry, the default registry is assumed.

The authorizationToken returned for each registry specified is a base64 encoded string that can be decoded and used in a docker login command to authenticate to a registry. The AWS CLI offers an aws ecr get-login command that simplifies the login process.
declarations.title: getAuthorizationToken

declarations.comments:
Retrieves the pre-signed Amazon S3 download URL corresponding to an image layer. You can only get URLs for image layers that are referenced in an image.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: getDownloadUrlForLayer

declarations.comments: Retrieves the specified lifecycle policy.
declarations.title: getLifecyclePolicy

declarations.comments: Retrieves the results of the specified lifecycle policy preview request.
declarations.title: getLifecyclePolicyPreview

declarations.comments: Retrieves the repository policy for a specified repository.
declarations.title: getRepositoryPolicy

declarations.comments:
Notify Amazon ECR that you intend to upload an image layer.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: initiateLayerUpload

declarations.comments:
Lists all the image IDs for a given repository.

You can filter images based on whether or not they are tagged by setting the tagStatus parameter to TAGGED or UNTAGGED. For example, you can filter your results to return only UNTAGGED images and then pipe that result to a BatchDeleteImage operation to delete them. Or, you can filter your results to return only TAGGED images to list all of the tags in your repository.
declarations.title: listImages

declarations.comments:
Creates or updates the image manifest and tags associated with an image.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: putImage

declarations.comments: Creates or updates a lifecycle policy. For information about lifecycle policy syntax, see Lifecycle Policy Template.
declarations.title: putLifecyclePolicy

declarations.comments: Applies a repository policy on a specified repository to control access permissions.
declarations.title: setRepositoryPolicy

declarations.comments: Starts a preview of the specified lifecycle policy. This allows you to see the results before creating the lifecycle policy.
declarations.title: startLifecyclePolicyPreview

declarations.comments:
Uploads an image layer part to Amazon ECR.

This operation is used by the Amazon ECR proxy, and it is not intended for general use by customers for pulling and pushing images. In most cases, you should use the docker CLI to pull, tag, and push images.
declarations.title: uploadLayerPart

declarations.comments: An object representing authorization data for an Amazon ECR registry.
declarations.title: AuthorizationData

declarations.comments: Deletes specified images within a specified repository. Images are specified with either the imageTag or imageDigest.
declarations.title: BatchDeleteImageRequest

declarations.comments: An object representing a filter on a DescribeImages operation.
declarations.title: DescribeImagesFilter

declarations.comments: The specified layer upload does not contain any layer parts.
declarations.title: EmptyUploadException

declarations.comments: An object representing an Amazon ECR image.
declarations.title: Image

declarations.comments: The specified image has already been pushed, and there were no changes to the manifest or image tag after the last push.

declarations.comments: An object representing an Amazon ECR image failure.

declarations.title: ImageNotFoundException

declarations.title: InvalidLayerException

declarations.comments: The layer part size is not valid, or the first byte specified is not consecutive to the last byte of a previous layer part upload.
declarations.title: InvalidLayerPartException

declarations.comments: The specified parameter is invalid. Review the available parameters for the API request.
declarations.title: InvalidParameterException

declarations.title: LayerInaccessibleException

declarations.comments: Layer parts must be at least 5 MiB in size.
declarations.title: LayerPartTooSmallException

declarations.comments: The specified layers could not be found, or the specified layer is not valid for this repository.
declarations.title: LayersNotFoundException

declarations.comments: The lifecycle policy could not be found, and no policy is set to the repository.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyNotFoundException

declarations.comments: The filter for the lifecycle policy preview.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyPreviewFilter

declarations.comments: The previous lifecycle policy preview request has not completed. Please try again later.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyPreviewInProgressException

declarations.comments: There is no dry run for this repository.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyPreviewNotFoundException

declarations.comments: The result of the lifecycle policy preview.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyPreviewResult

declarations.comments: The summary of the lifecycle policy preview request.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyPreviewSummary

declarations.comments: The type of action to be taken.
declarations.title: LifecyclePolicyRuleAction

declarations.comments: The operation did not succeed because it would have exceeded a service limit for your account. For more information, see Amazon ECR Default Service Limits in the Amazon Elastic Container Registry User Guide.
declarations.title: LimitExceededException

declarations.comments: An object representing a filter on a ListImages operation.
declarations.title: ListImagesFilter

declarations.comments: An object representing a repository.
declarations.title: Repository

declarations.comments: The specified repository already exists in the specified registry.
declarations.title: RepositoryAlreadyExistsException

declarations.comments: The specified repository contains images. To delete a repository that contains images, you must force the deletion with the force parameter.
declarations.title: RepositoryNotEmptyException

declarations.comments: The specified repository could not be found. Check the spelling of the specified repository and ensure that you are performing operations on the correct registry.
declarations.title: RepositoryNotFoundException

declarations.comments: The specified repository and registry combination does not have an associated repository policy.
declarations.title: RepositoryPolicyNotFoundException

declarations.comments: These errors are usually caused by a server-side issue.
declarations.title: ServerException

declarations.comments: The upload could not be found, or the specified upload id is not valid for this repository.
declarations.title: UploadNotFoundException
